entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Backfill history signals for shortcut matches
entry.content:
Some shortcuts aren't deduped with history matches. This happens when:

- The corresponding history entry was crowded out by other history

matches.

- The corresponding history entry had expired and was removed from the

history DB, but the shortcut remained because it was bookmarked.

- The corresponding history entry was never created because the match

was a built-in match such as chrome://settings .



In those cases, the shortcut has shortcut signals, and possibly bookmark

signals, but no history signals. E.g. a shortcut might have 10 shortcut

visits, but 0 typed and total visits.



That threw the ML model off. Shortcuts missing history signals were

scored lower the more shortcut visits they had. So if the user wanted to

navigate to chrome://settings/x, the more they navigated to it, the more

likely it was it would not be defaulted.



This CL backfills the history signals for shortcuts. E.g. typed visits =

total visits = shortcut visits.



This doesn't affect shortcuts with history entries; the backfilled

shortcut match's history signals will be merged with the history match's

history signals.



Bug: 1405555

entry.title: [gbb-cct] Initial fix for janky scrolling.
entry.content:
Previously we could auto-trigger while the user was scrolling the page - this led to some jank in scrolling, as unfortunately the operation to initialise the bottom sheet is quite heavy.



This CL provides an initial fix for this by waiting for scroll motion to be ended before auto-triggering. To mitigate the reduction in peek frequency caused by this change, the CL also refactors to allow fetching of data (which does not actually hold up the UI thread - it is delegated to a background thread) at an earlier stage, even before the top bar is hidden or motion is ended.



The CL also adds a couple of checks to avoid some edge cases (e.g. network fetch returns after a new page has been loaded).

entry.title: [EditContext] Ensure that ExecutionContext of the associated element is used
entry.content:
Currently if an author tries to associate an EditContext with an

Element in a document that's different from the document where it was

constructed, the EditContext will make the associated element editable

but not capture text input. The reason is that in

`EditContext::Focus()`,

the call to do `GetInputMethodController().SetActiveEditContext(this)`

is getting the InputMethodController for the ExecutionContext that

the EditContext was constructed with, not the InputMethodController

for the document the EditContext is now associated with. So to the

InputMethodController that ends up receiving the text input, it

looks like there is no active EditContext.



Fix this by updating the EditContext's ExecutionContext whenever an

associated element is set.



An alternative considered was to have EditContext no longer store

the ExecutionContext directly at all and instead always get it from

the associated element. However there are some cases where this is

problematic. For example when DispatchTextFormatEvent is called

immediately before DispatchCompositionEndEvent, the EditContext

could be detached from its element in the textformatupdate

handler, which would then cause problems in

DispatchCompositionEndEvent since it uses the ExecutionContext

via the DomWindow() call.

entry.title: [Site search policy] Support for site search in TemplateURL
entry.content:
This CL makes the following changes to `TemplateURL` for the new

SiteSearchSettings Enterprise policy:

- Add a new field `featured_by_policy` to indicate when a SE should

be featured in the Omnibox

- Changes the type of field `created_by_policy` from a boolean to

an enum to represent which policy introduced the SE:

- 0 = no policy

- 1 = Default Search Provider policy

- 2 = Site Search policy



This is the downstream effect in the keywords DB table:

- Add a new column corresponding to `featured_by_policy`

- Change the code that reads and writes entries to the table to

convert to/from the enum instead of a boolean



There is no need to change the table schema for the `created_by_policy`

field, because the corresponding column is already an integer with

the same representation as above (0: no policy, 1: DSP policy).



Screenshots: b/307544344#comment5



We were originally planning to only add `featured_by_policy` to `TemplateURL`, but unfortunately that doesn't allow us to

differentiate from the default search provider set by policy:



- Today, there are two booleans to represent policy state:

`created_by_policy` (DSP policy) and `enforced_by_policy` (whether

the policy is required or recommended)

- Those two booleans represent 3 valid states: no policy, policy is

mandatory, policy is recommended

- The site search policy is mandatory only in the initial version, but

we may eventually support the recommended state -> that will require

us to support more states than currently possible



Please refer to crrev.com/c/5017736 for a discussion on alternatives.

entry.title: Add an enabled-by-default flag for iframe support of adAuctionHeaders.
entry.content:
The iframe support for adAuctionHeaders is still guarded by the

`kFledgeNegativeTargeting` flag, and this remains the flag that controls

the enablement of the `adAuctionHeaders` attribute on the iframe element.

However, we add a separate `kEnableIFrameAdAuctionHeaders` flag that can

be disabled to remove iframe navigation handling of the ad auction

response headers. When `kEnableIFrameAdAuctionHeaders` is disabled, the `Ad-Auction-Signals` and `Ad-Auction-Additional-Bid` response headers are still cleared for iframes that specify the `adAuctionHeaders` attribute, but this has no user-visible impact because iframe navigation offers no programmatic access to the response headers.

entry.title: Consistently clear sync metadata on SyncMode changes
entry.content:
Sync metadata should usually be cleared when Sync is stopped, and any

left-behind metadata should eventually get cleaned up - and after

crbug.com/897628, that was generally the case. But there was one edge

case that wasn't handled yet: When the Sync machinery missed a switch

between "full Sync" (aka Sync-the-feature) and transport mode, the

metadata of the "other" (now-inactive) mode would be left behind and

not cleaned up.

This CL fixes this by doing two things:

* Adding ClearMetadataWhileStopped() calls (on both delegates i.e.

processors) in ModelLoadManager::LoadModels(), after the correct

delegate was started.

* Changing the semantics of ClearMetadataWhileStopped() so that it's

a no-op if the type in question is not actually stopped.

Together, this means the metadata of the "wrong" mode gets cleared,

without affecting the metadata of the "correct" mode.
